Merge pull request #489 from CodeKingdomsTeam/no-button-role

Don't add role=button to scriptEditor div

Don't add role=button to scriptEditor div as this prevents screen readers from using ARIA roles of elements in the external editor iframe. For example any divs with role=alert are not read by the screen reader with this parent as role=button

Fix truncated change numbers in history list

In the "history" list, the change number (#0, #1, etc.) appears after the script name.  For long-ish script names (like "astonishing Jetpack Jumper"), the name is truncated which removes the change number. This fix moves the change number before the script name, so it is still visible if the name is truncated.

Blocks: new set of blocks for music.

The user can now play music on P0 using the Blocks interface.
- A "play note" block has been added, which takes a note and a duration.
- Standard notes (A to G) have been added; standard durations (whole note all
  the way to 16th note) have been added too.
- The default tempo is 60 (~ 60ms for a whole note if my computations are
  correct). The kids can set the "whole note" variable (in ms) from the blocks
  interface if they wish to override the default. If they want to set the "whole
  note" variable using a tempo, the formula is:

      whole note := 4 * 1000 / tempo

New name management system for the C++ code emitter.

TouchDevelop allows any sort of identifier, meaning that if we do a nave
translation, there may be name collisions (e.g. "foo$" and "foo@" may both map
to C++ identifier "foo_"). The new system clarifies the assumptions and tries to
both keep readable names *and* avoid collisions.

The may still be collisions in the following cases, where we keep a simple
scheme (i.e. replace non-alphanumeric characters with "_"):
- two libraries in the same script that map to the same C++ identifier (e.g.
  "lib@" and "lib$"),
- two fields in the same object definition (e.g. "field$" and "field@").

Other than that, collisions for function names, global variable names, object
types, and local variables are happily handled.

New type inference algorithms for Blocks.

This implements a proper Hindley-Milner style unification algorithm for block
scripts. [compiler.ts] now contains a (classic), path-compressing union-find
data structure. Type variables are now properly unified for polymorphic
comparison blocks ("=" block).

Whenever a block is missing, a "placeholder" block is (temporarily) put in
place, with a unification variable attached to it. At code-generation time, a
default value is provided according to the type. After code-generation, the
placeholder blocks are removed.

Blockly compiler.

Type-checking of blockly programs + error reporting.

All the blocks have been tagged with a type, including the "device" ones. The
types are: Boolean, Number, String, Image. The expected type is propagated down
when compiling the blocks. When there is a type mismatch, the block cannot be
compiled, so it is highlighted, an error is reported in the UI, and the user is
provided with a "force compile" / "force graduate" button along with an error
message (UI to be refined).

Normally, the very UI of Blockly prevents type mismatches (blocks themselves
have a basic type system). For instance, one cannot compare numbers and strings
(the block will just "pop out" when trying to do that). However, Blockly does
not perform type inference of variables. Therefore, our compiler performs a
quick & dirty type-checking pass that tries to infer the type of variables,
using a really dumb fixpoint computation (given the typical size of Blockly
programs, it probably does not warrant writing a Hindley-Milner inference system
in Typescript).

All blockly variables are now compiled as globals, except for loop indices,
which are compiled as usual. Loop indices that are assigned to generate a global
along with a while loop, meaning that the translation remains correct.

client code should retry a save operation; that is, [!retry] means that by the
time the client code examines the [PostUserInstalledResponse], the cloud
contains the same version that's available locally.
